description: Developed multi-INT sensor resource management algorithms which produced optimal, synchronized C4ISR collection plans and sensor schedules). This tool maximizes target collection value subject to tasking and platform collection performance estimates and constraints over planning horizons of typically up to 24 hours in duration. These constraints typically included collection time windows, collection quality, operating/no fly zones, and threat exposure. These systems include high altitude airborne platforms, standoff collectors, medium-to-low altitude UAVs and space borne platforms, and include a mix of sensors such as ELINT, COMINT, IMINT (EO/IR) and SAR/GMTI radar. Specifically, he implemented and tested high fidelity geolocation models (AOA, TDOA, FDOA) together with these planning algorithms. He also investigated transitioning this planning tool to several programs including Space Radar, the MC2A/E-10A next-generation sensor platform, the Distributed Common Ground System, as well as various overhead sensor system architectures. As Principal Investigator for a Phase II Small Business Innovative Research (SBIR) effort, integrated the above planning tool with a Multiple Hypothesis Tracker used for ground moving targets with MTI Radar sensors. The tracker/sensor resource manager component generates task cues for the planning component, which, in turn, provides updated platform routes to the sensor resource manager. As Principal Investigator for another Phase II SBIR, investigated the use of hierarchical target valuation algorithms based for both Level I and II fusion information (groups of objects, such as convoys) in a sensor resource manager, which chooses both sensor pointing direction and mode (MTI, HRR, SAR) based on future sensor/state predictions provided by Finite State Markov models. He also produced an algorithm description document for a multiple-platform SIGINT AOA geolocation algorithm and produced a prototype version of this algorithm in MATLAB.

description: He developed/modified in-house orbit determination analysis software, which was used to reduce on-orbit errors using Extended Kalman Filtering techniques. This software, which is written in C++, processes ground range, GPS range, as well as other difference measurements in order to provide an improved real-time orbit determination and geolocation capability. He performed a detailed model validation and comparison with the FORTRAN version of this package, modified the range and GPS measurement models for a new application, and assisted with the interface to the orbit determination workstation, which was to provide real-time measurements. He wrote a signal simulator and signal processor using X-Midas macros and primitives that was used to improve operational signal processing and analysis capabilities. He participated in a three-week operational test and validation of these algorithms at an operational site and gathered additional data for analysis. He also performed modeling and simulation tasks that directly supported systems engineering and integration efforts related to current and future overhead and processing architectures using an object-oriented discrete event simulator. Specific tasks included serving as analyst, and later task lead, on an internal analytic exercise that evaluated the ability of the simulation software to model SIGINT collection performance, including link closure performance analyses. Later, he modified "back-end" (processing/exploitation-related) models that were used to provide results to several allied study partners that estimated the performance of future processing architectures. He later moved to the development team, where he was responsible for software systems engineering, requirements development (including the development of the Systems Requirements Document (SRD)), CONOPS development, and detailed initial design for a new, object-oriented simulator that was designed to process multi-INT signals.

description: Was responsible for system performance, simulation design, and software engineering test and evaluation efforts related to accuracy model development and analysis activities associated with the TRIDENT Submarine Launched Ballistic Missile weapon and navigation systems. These efforts included the development of a weapon-system level accuracy model, which determined the effect of errors in navigation, fire control, guidance, deployment, reentry, and operational and environmental conditions on total weapon system accuracy. Development of this model was very closely related to the missile flight test program. The model was used to conduct pre-flight accuracy predictive analysis for both pad and submarine-launched flight tests. Also, he performed post-flight analyses by processing data (based on cumulative flight test program accuracy as well as stellar sighting observables) from these tests and reviewing "quick look" test reports. The weapon system accuracy model was also used to conduct accuracy improvement sensitivity studies and to estimate the accuracy of the deployed tactical system. Was also responsible for the design, development, and maintenance of a navigation error covariance simulation, which provided an estimate of several types of submarine navigation errors (gyros, accelerometers, velocity references, filters, vertical deflection (gravity)) on overall weapon system accuracy using applied optimal estimation (Kalman Filtering) techniques. This simulation was used to conduct a variety of navigation accuracy sensitivity analysis studies.

We know that situational awareness, two-way communication, and custom organizational processes are vital in responding to network security issues, management of critical resources, and in getting maximum return on investment. CMS values people, relationships, and the pursuit of mission success. Convergent Mission Solutions provides management of cyber security professionals and critical operations center functions, so government entities can focus on the strategic issues that move the organization forward. Technologies are converging, just as the skills required to respond to cyber threats. The mechanisms to protect critical infrastructure and refine network defense procedures need synchronization that align with strategic missions, resources, and capabilities. Whether an existing staff requires course correction, or building a program from the ground up, CMS aligns strategic vision to the operational execution. We work to create a cyber security operation that converges with the mission, using our unique capabilities. We take a common sense approach to solving problems, realizing that time is important, when responding to a network security incident. Knowledge of Tiered CND services and expectations, compliance to DoD certification requirements, shaping programs to support ongoing network defense, sharing knowledge for professional teaming, and succession planning are critical for producing net-defenders, today….and into the future. Will Farmer, a retired Air Force Veteran, with extensive leadership and management experience, leads CMS. He translates network defense client's strategic vision into operational context, and links CMS services to the mission.

Primarily responsible for synchronizing, de-conflicting and coordinating combined and joint fires planning for the Combined Forces Commander (CFC); determines, authors and disseminates guidance for targeting priorities, target nomination, and theater fire support processes. Manages 25,000 targets on the Joint Target List (JTL), Restricted Target List (RTL), and No Strike List (NSL) for the entire theater of Korea. Synchronizes and integrates efforts across numerous staff working groups in support of theater lethal and non-lethal fires. Synchronizes cyber targeting effects with maneuver unit operations in support of the CFC Commanders operational plan. Action Officer responsible for managing the Joint Targeting Coordination Board (JTCB), Targeting Effects Working Group (TEWG) and the Targeting Special Effects Working Group (TSEWG); events which drive targeting efforts supporting war fighting operations for 30,000 U.S. Soldiers and 600,000 Republic of Korea Soldiers throughout the Greater Seoul Metropolitan Area (GSMA). Advises and mentors Korean field grade officers of the Ground Component Command (GCC) targeting cell on target nomination; Billing Official for responsible for $36000 budget.

description: Support U.S. Special Forces Command, Pacific (SOCPAC). As a subordinate unified command of USPACOM, SOCPAC and its component units deploy throughout the Pacific, supporting USPACOM's Theater Security Cooperation Program, deliberate plans, and real world contingencies. SOCPAC elements annually conduct small unit exchanges, joint and combined training events, and operational deployments throughout the Pacific, fostering interoperability with host nation partners and facilitating strategic and operational objectives. Subordinate elements play a major role in ongoing counterdrug and humanitarian demining operations, training host nation forces in Thailand, Laos, Cambodia, Vietnam, the Philippines, and other Theater countries. SOCPAC also hosts an annual Pacific Area Special Operations Conference in Hawaii, which attracts over 200 U.S. and foreign delegates and provides unique information exchange opportunities. The command maintains a honed capability to operate as a rapidly deployable Joint Task Force (JTF). In January 2002, soon after terrorists attacked the United States, SOCPAC deployed to the Southern Philippines as JTF 510, conducting counterterrorist operations with the Philippine Government under Operation ENDURING FREEDOM. JTF 510 redeployed on 1 September 2002, leaving stay-behind elements to form Joint Special Operations Task Force-Philippines and continue operations with the Armed Forces of the Philippines. Today, SOCPAC forces are operating in multiple high-priority Pacific Theater countries, increasing partner nation capabilities to defeat international terrorism, improving cultural understanding, and fully prepared to meet emerging threats.

title: Account Executive
name: Ken Stoni
description: Leading Esri’s National Government Sectors effort to create a ‘Geospatial Framework for Cybersecurity’. The goal is to help organizations detect complex cyber intrusions earlier (those that integrate cyber and physical effects) and respond to them appropriately and with agility. To enable effective collaboration, organizations need a mechanism to integrate all available data in order to quickly discover and prioritize cyber threats to their most critical processes. Many existing cybersecurity frameworks do an excellent job of describing the ‘who’, ‘what’, ‘why’ and ‘how’ to apply controls-- what seems to be missing is any indication of ‘when’ and ‘where’ to focus existing capabilities. Not specifying a means of prioritization could result in the reactive and ad-hoc implementation of controls leaving exploitable holes in an organization’s cyber defenses. All human activity, to include cyber, can be plotted in space/time so geospatial information systems (GIS) provide an excellent foundation for modeling the effects of interdisciplinary activities. The framework being developed by Esri uses its existing Platform technology and a unique concept – the ‘cyber supply line’ – to integrate mission requirements, data flows, facilities and technology into a GIS-based common operational picture. This could allow any organization to make better use of the cybersecurity data and tools in which it has already invested. The model could also facilitate the incorporation of advanced technology and techniques over time.

description: Global Analysis Operations is an independently functioning entity within BAE Systems. In the United States, BAE Systems has more than 55,000 employees, including 7,000 employees in the Washington, D.C. area who support members of the intelligence community. Global Intelligence & Operations has unrestricted access to the abundant resources and full support of the company. Mission-focused and mission-centered, Global Intelligence & Operations (GI&O) provides all-source analytic support, including multi-intelligence analysis and training, to the U.S. government and federal, state and local agencies focusing on national and homeland security. Keeping pace with the complex threats in today’s evolving international environment, BAE Systems provides support to the defense and intelligence communities in collection support, gaming, research, open course, cyber threat analysis, law enforcement analysis, intelligence, surveillance and reconnaissance analysis, tradecraft advancement and socio-cultural analysis. The defense and intelligence communities are at the cutting edge of emerging technology, procedures and policy of the ever-expanding intelligence, surveillance and reconnaissance (ISR) field and BAE Systems is their foremost partner. GI&O is dedicated to providing analytic services to the U.S. government. We are the go-to company for full-motion video analysis, motion imagery analysis, and geospatial analysis, as well as providing analytical support to new technology to make it more useful in the field. This unique, cross-cutting analytic business model makes us effective to meet our customers changing requirements, sets us up for continued growth, and helps employees to meet their career aspirations.

description: DomPrep is a thought-leadership information service for the preparedness community. Created in 1998, DomPrep offers content – provided by practitioners, subject matter experts, and DomPrep40 Advisors – to more than 20,000 first responders, medical receivers, emergency planners, local-state-federal authorities, and private-sector professionals. The DomPrep40 is an interactive advisory board of insider practitioners and opinion leaders who have been asked to offer advice and recommendations on pertinent issues of the day. Focusing primarily on all-hazard preparedness as well as response and recovery operations, they will be challenged to provide quantifiable feedback that will be shared with the DomPrep audience.

title: VP Strategic Business Development
name: Jerry Evans
description: Responsible for providing leadership to further develop company's core competences by working with clients, the market, and functional leaders to grow footprint in target accounts. Delivered technical and functional expertise to support the analysis of key systems and initiatives within the DoD and federal community. As part of my role I provide guidance and training to help change the current culture from a small business mindset to that of a large. I encourage early BD and capture planning activities as a crucial aspect in winning, and show how by investing time, energy, and resources early during the BD and capture planning phases, Kingfisher minimizes risk and mitigates poor pursuit decisions that can become a drain on corporate businesses resources. I have also been able to show how effective early BD and capture planning reduces overall proposal-development costs, and improves win rates.

title: Director, Business Development, Intelligence Support Services
name: Jerry Evans
description: Director, Business Development and Capture Manager for all Intelligence Services contracts to include, Imagery Analysis (IA) All-Source Intelligence, HUMINT, CI/CT and Atmospheric contracts. I was responsible for Business Development and Capture Management activities for all proposal efforts in the Intelligence Analysis fields. My primary responsibility was positioning, vetting, qualifying, capturing and winning prime contracts with an Intelligence focus such as: the $300M - Iraq Advisory, Atmospheric and Analysis Support Services contract (A3S2); 185M - Atmospheric Program – Afghanistan (AP-A); and the 19M - CJ2X CI/HUMINT Support Services – Afghanistan. My secondary responsibility is to continue building our Intel qualifications through teaming with industry partners on additional Intelligence opportunities such as: BAE for the DIA SIA C-IED Task Order; SAIC for the NGA EPASS Imagery contract; CACI for the GBPS contract for overall support to the US Special Operations Command; SKC for the DIA CI/HUMINT Enterprise Management opportunity; and BAE for the ESMARTS contract for NGA.

title: Director, National Security Programs
name: Jerry Evans
description: Director of National Security Programs for all Intelligence Services; Imagery Analysis (IA) All-Source Intelligence, HUMINT and CI/CT contracts providing Program/Project Management support in the areas of Staffing, budgeting, Schedule performance and monthly reporting to Government and Prime Customers. As Director, I was responsible for Business Development and Capture Management for all proposal efforts in the Intelligence Analysis fields. Responsible for vetting and marketing Prime contractors for teaming on the DIA Solutions for Intelligence Analysis (SIA) opportunity and NGA SMARTS contract, which concluded with signed Teaming Agreements on both. Assembled a Small Business Team for the upcoming DIA SITE opportunity, where I was responsible for marketing and signing a Teaming Agreement with the largest current DIESCON Large Business Prime as a subcontractor to our team.

title: ISC
name: Jerry Evans
description: Reserve All Source/HUMIT Analysts to DIA from 2004- 2008 (Retired) My last assignment before I retired was with the DIA Defense Attaché Unit supporting various middle east Embassy mission requirements with HUMINT Targeting and All source Intelligence utilizing IMINT, SIGINT and HUMINT products in support of the Global War on Terrorism. Reserve Imagery Analyst support to NIMA/NGA from 1999- 2004 Supported the stand up of the first Reserve Unit for NIMA/NGA and provided Imagery Analysis support to NOC-P and the Navy Yard as a Senior Imagery Analyst. I was responsible for providing back up support on 1st phase reporting on all Naval, Air and Missile OOB and EEI requirements for NOC-I and all Combatant Commands. Daily use of Light Tables, IEC, NES, RMS, WARP, MET, ArcView, ERDAS and IDEX II. • Recalled to active duty with the Navy to support Operation Enduring Freedom/Nobel Eagle from October 2001 to April 2002 as a Senior Imagery Analyst supporting the National Imagery and Mapping Agency (NIMA)/NGA Operations Center - Pentagon (NOC-P). Directly supported the Joint Chiefs of Staff, National Command Authorities and personally produced 4 imagery graphics that were briefed to the President. Attended various briefings and training on future systems and the U.S. Imagery and Geospacial Systems Architecture, and the Future Imagery Architecture (FIA). Personally produced over 12 NIIBs and 100+ NES Remarks during my recall to active duty. • Responsible for global I&W (Indications & Warnings), situational awareness, combat assessment, in direct support of the SecDef (Secretary of Defense), JCS (Joint Chiefs of Staff), SecAF (Secretary of the Air Force), CSAF (Chief of Staff of the Air Force), and Chief of Staff of the Army, in direct support to the J2 Targeting Cell, and CENTCOM. Working cooperatively as a team member in a stressful crisis environment, providing 24/7 imagery analysis support to the NOC-P.

description: Director of National Security Programs for all Intelligence Services; Imagery Analysis (IA) All-Source Intelligence, HUMINT and CI/CT contracts providing Program/Project Management support in the areas of Staffing, budgeting, Schedule performance and monthly reporting to Government and Prime Customers. As Director, I was responsible for Business Development and Capture Management for all proposal efforts in the Intelligence Analysis fields. Responsible for vetting and marketing Prime contractors for teaming on the DIA Solutions for Intelligence Analysis (SIA) opportunity and NGA SMARTS contract, which concluded with signed Teaming Agreements on both. Assembled a Small Business Team for the upcoming DIA SITE opportunity, where I was responsible for marketing and signing a Teaming Agreement with the largest current DIESCON Large Business Prime as a subcontractor to our team.

title: ISC
name: Jerry Evans
description: Reserve All Source/HUMIT Analysts to DIA from 2004- 2008 (Retired) My last assignment before I retired was with the DIA Defense Attaché Unit supporting various middle east Embassy mission requirements with HUMINT Targeting and All source Intelligence utilizing IMINT, SIGINT and HUMINT products in support of the Global War on Terrorism. Reserve Imagery Analyst support to NIMA/NGA from 1999- 2004 Supported the stand up of the first Reserve Unit for NIMA/NGA and provided Imagery Analysis support to NOC-P and the Navy Yard as a Senior Imagery Analyst. I was responsible for providing back up support on 1st phase reporting on all Naval, Air and Missile OOB and EEI requirements for NOC-I and all Combatant Commands. Daily use of Light Tables, IEC, NES, RMS, WARP, MET, ArcView, ERDAS and IDEX II. • Recalled to active duty with the Navy to support Operation Enduring Freedom/Nobel Eagle from October 2001 to April 2002 as a Senior Imagery Analyst supporting the National Imagery and Mapping Agency (NIMA)/NGA Operations Center - Pentagon (NOC-P). Directly supported the Joint Chiefs of Staff, National Command Authorities and personally produced 4 imagery graphics that were briefed to the President. Attended various briefings and training on future systems and the U.S. Imagery and Geospacial Systems Architecture, and the Future Imagery Architecture (FIA). Personally produced over 12 NIIBs and 100+ NES Remarks during my recall to active duty. • Responsible for global I&W (Indications & Warnings), situational awareness, combat assessment, in direct support of the SecDef (Secretary of Defense), JCS (Joint Chiefs of Staff), SecAF (Secretary of the Air Force), CSAF (Chief of Staff of the Air Force), and Chief of Staff of the Army, in direct support to the J2 Targeting Cell, and CENTCOM. Working cooperatively as a team member in a stressful crisis environment, providing 24/7 imagery analysis support to the NOC-P.

title: VP Strategic Business Development
name: Jerry Evans
description: Responsible for providing leadership to further develop company's core competences by working with clients, the market, and functional leaders to grow footprint in target accounts. Delivered technical and functional expertise to support the analysis of key systems and initiatives within the DoD and federal community. As part of my role I provide guidance and training to help change the current culture from a small business mindset to that of a large. I have also been able to show how effective early BD and capture planning reduces overall proposal-development costs, and improves win rates.

title: Director, Business Development, Intelligence Support Services
name: Jerry Evans
description: Director, Business Development and Capture Manager for all Intelligence Services contracts to include, Imagery Analysis (IA) All-Source Intelligence, HUMINT, CI/CT and Atmospheric contracts. I was responsible for Business Development and Capture Management activities for all proposal efforts in the Intelligence Analysis fields. My primary responsibility was positioning, vetting, qualifying, capturing and winning prime contracts with an Intelligence focus such as: the $300M - Iraq Advisory, Atmospheric and Analysis Support Services contract (A3S2); 185M - Atmospheric Program – Afghanistan (AP-A); and the 19M - CJ2X CI/HUMINT Support Services – Afghanistan. My secondary responsibility is to continue building our Intel qualifications through teaming with industry partners on additional Intelligence opportunities such as: BAE for the DIA SIA C-IED Task Order; SAIC for the NGA EPASS Imagery contract; CACI for the GBPS contract for overall support to the US Special Operations Command; SKC for the DIA CI/HUMINT Enterprise Management opportunity; and BAE for the ESMARTS contract for NGA.

Daily use of Light Tables, IEC, NES, RMS, WARP, MET, ArcView, ERDAS and IDEX II. • Recalled to active duty with the Navy to support Operation Enduring Freedom/Nobel Eagle from October 2001 to April 2002 as a Senior Imagery Analyst supporting the National Imagery and Mapping Agency (NIMA)/NGA Operations Center - Pentagon (NOC-P). Directly supported the Joint Chiefs of Staff, National Command Authorities and personally produced 4 imagery graphics that were briefed to the President. Attended various briefings and training on future systems and the U.S. Imagery and Geospacial Systems Architecture, and the Future Imagery Architecture (FIA). Personally produced over 12 NIIBs and 100+ NES Remarks during my recall to active duty. • Responsible for global I&W (Indications & Warnings), situational awareness, combat assessment, in direct support of the SecDef (Secretary of Defense), JCS (Joint Chiefs of Staff), SecAF (Secretary of the Air Force), CSAF (Chief of Staff of the Air Force), and Chief of Staff of the Army, in direct support to the J2 Targeting Cell, and CENTCOM. Working cooperatively as a team member in a stressful crisis environment, providing 24/7 imagery analysis support to the NOC-P.
